<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06231084 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06231084 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (3); PHOTO: The top look for girls: leggings. Also hot are the polkadots on the leggings and flowered trapeze top from Cherokee. (color); PHOTO:Fashionable for fall: denim, graffiti prints and florals. All from J.C.Penney. At right is a fanny pack from Woolworth's. (color); PHOTO: (lunch box)(color)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; SCHOOL; FASHION; TREND  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  SCHOOL clothing this fall is elementary. Boys can pop on a pair of overallswith a Hypercolor T-shirt while girls can shimmy into skinny leggings and abig top. Both can grab anything plaid and be assured of looking good on theplayground.;    It's a season of key elements, with an emphasis on comfort.While adults may be willing to constrict themselves for the sake of highstyle, children will not. That's one reason tight jeans are giving way tolooser silhouettes.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CLASS ACTSTHIS FALL, KIDS CAN GO TO THE FRONT OF THECLASS IN CLOTHING BY REMEMBERING A FEW KEYELEMENTS -- AND KEEPING COMFORTABLE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Cover Story(box) The latest fad: Leave price tags on your clothes(box) Retailers pay more attention to large sizes(box) Take the frustration out of shopping, Page 6LAdditional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Here's a look at the five easy pieces that are the cornerstone of thisyear's stylish school look.; PLAID;    Just as the adult fashion world is on amad plaid go-round, so is the youth market. For boys, it's most obvious inshirts and jackets, while girls have the option of plaid dresses, skirts,jumpers and even leggings.;    &quot;The No. 1 fashion statement for boys this yearis plaid,&quot; says Diane Giraco, merchandise manager for Cherokee Youth Wear.&quot;Whether it's buffalo checks or tartan, plaid is very big.&quot;; OVERALLS;    Thisis a look that's filtering down to youngsters from their older siblings.Overalls are oversized, often worn with one strap hooked and the other hangingloose. In addition to overalls, there are versions with shorts (shortalls) andskirts (skirtalls).;    &quot;Overalls are very big for boys,&quot; says Jackie NollDunn, spokeswoman for the children's division of J.C. Penney. &quot;Their clothingis being influenced by rap music. The look is urban city, but mixed withneutral colors and a lot of prints that are graffiti inspired.&quot;; HYPERCOLOR;   Heat-sensitive T-shirts that change color with body temperature are hot, hot,hot. Place a hand on a mauve top and you'll see it outlined in pink. Blow on apurple shirt and you'll see a blue spot. The T-shirts are from Seattle-basedGenerra Sportswear, which has an exclusive on the process outside of Japan,where it was invented.;    &quot;It's kind of gimmicky, but kids like the colorchange,&quot; says Kurt Buchholz, vice president and merchandise manager forchildren at Macy's. &quot;Sales have been phenomenal.&quot;; LEGGINGS;    If there's onesingle look for little girls, it's leggings worn with a baby doll dress or bigtop. The pieces are easily coordinated -- print leggings with a solid top,prints top and bottom or solid leggings with a print top. Popular prints areflorals, plaids, dots, paisleys and stripes.;    Asked to name the single&quot;must-have&quot; wardrobe item for girls, Sears spokeswoman Marci Schaffer says,&quot;Peplum tops with print leggings.&quot;; DENIM;    A wardrobe staple, the news indenim this year is in styles such as overalls, new colors like black or greenand prints, particularly floral prints for girls.;    &quot;The five-pocket denimjean&quot; is the one to look for with boys, says Rebecca Mack, corporatecommunications manager for Mervyn's.; ADDITIONAL ELEMENTS;    Key as thesefive looks are, there are others for fall worth checking out. For boys:wrestler-style pants, clothing with sporting team motifs, baseball caps, sweatshirts and longer shorts. Girls: dresses, ethnic prints, scarf necklines andblack mixed with bright shades of purple, jade or fuchsia.; THE LUNCH BOX:ACCESSORY NECESSITY;    ALMOST as important as what to wear the first day ofschool is which lunch box to carry. If you make a mistake with clothing, youdon't have to face it every day, but there's no such luck with schoolsupplies.;    Trends in lunch boxes, pencil sharpeners, notebooks, pens andfanny packs include:;    (box) Teen-age Mutant Ninja Turtles. Thosepizza-loving guys with the Renaissance names just won't go away.;    (box) TheLittle Mermaid. Ariel's appeal is enduring.;    (box) Ecology themes,reflecting youngsters' continuing concerns with animals such as zebras, lionsand sea turtles.;    (box) Sports teams. Local or national, allegiances areforged at an early age.;    (box) Graffiti designs. Abstract and colorful.;   (box) Classics. There are some themes that are eternal with the younger set,including Mickey Mouse, dinosaurs and cuddly kittens.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Stories by Mary Gottschalk  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910818  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1L  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  743  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday August 18, 199100231084,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>